---
<SiteLayout site="siliconbased" title={meta.title} description={meta.description} canonical="https://siliconbased.dev/cast-of-the-terminal-list-dark-wolf" schema={schema}>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>Cast of The Terminal List: Dark Wolf</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">Exploring the elite operators and intelligence agents in the highly anticipated spin-off prequel series.</p>
    </div>

    <article>
      <section>
        <h2>Expanding Jack Carr's Universe</h2>
        <p>
          Following the immense success of <em>The Terminal List</em>, based on the thrilling novel by former Navy SEAL Jack Carr, the universe expands with a highly anticipated spin-off prequel: <em>The Terminal List: Dark Wolf</em>. This new series shifts the focus away from the immediate aftermath of James Reece's tragic loss, instead exploring the formative years of these elite operators and their complex operations before the devastating events of the original series.
        </p>
        <p>
          At the heart of any gripping military thriller is the talent bringing the tactical operations and political espionage to life. The <strong>cast of the terminal list: dark wolf</strong> features returning fan favorites alongside significant new additions. This guide breaks down the main operators, the intelligence agents they work with, and what these casting choices mean for the narrative direction of the prequel.
        </p>
      </section>

      <div class="callout">
        <h3>The Core Concept: A Prequel Perspective</h3>
        <p>
          Because <em>Dark Wolf</em> is a prequel, the dynamics between characters are drastically different than in the original series. Viewers will see Ben Edwards and James Reece as tight-knit brothers-in-arms, long before the betrayal that defined their relationship in <em>The Terminal List</em>. This timeline allows the cast to explore the trust and camaraderie that makes their eventual fallout so tragic.
        </p>
      </div>

      <section>
        <h2>The Main Cast: The Operators</h2>
        <p>
          The primary cast of <em>Dark Wolf</em> focuses on the lethal operators of the US Navy SEALs, diving deep into their operations and personal lives.
        </p>

        <h3>Taylor Kitsch as Ben Edwards</h3>
        <p>
          Taylor Kitsch steps into the primary spotlight as Chief Special Warfare Operator Benjamin "Ben" Edwards (a.k.a. Charlie Zero-Two/0-2). In the original series, Edwards was a CIA Ground Branch operative with a complex, ultimately antagonistic relationship with James Reece. <em>Dark Wolf</em> explores Edwards's time as a Troop Chief in Charlie Platoon, SEAL Team 5, detailing his journey from a frontline operator to his controversial transition into the murky world of the CIA. Kitsch's portrayal provides a nuanced look at a man navigating the gray areas of global conflict.
        </p>

        <h3>Tom Hopper as Raife Hastings</h3>
        <p>
          A highly anticipated addition to the <strong>cast of the terminal list: dark wolf</strong> is Tom Hopper (<em>The Umbrella Academy</em>, <em>Black Sails</em>) as Lieutenant Raife Hastings (a.k.a. Charlie Zero-One/0-1). Hastings is a US Navy SEAL and the Troop Commander of Charlie Platoon. A character deeply embedded in Jack Carr's lore, Hastings has familial connections to the legendary Selous Scouts of Rhodesia. Hopper brings an imposing physical presence and a commanding aura to the role of a seasoned combat veteran who operates by his own strict moral code.
        </p>

        <h3>Chris Pratt as James Reece</h3>
        <p>
          Chris Pratt reprises his role as Lieutenant James Reece (a.k.a. Alpha Zero-One/0-1), a US Navy SEAL and Troop Commander of Alpha Platoon, SEAL Team 7. While the original series focused on Reece's vengeance, <em>Dark Wolf</em> presents Reece in his prime—a focused, dedicated leader deeply bonded with his teammates. Pratt's inclusion ensures continuity with the flagship series while allowing him to explore a less traumatized, more mission-focused version of the character.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Recurring Cast: Intelligence and Espionage</h2>
        <p>
          The operators on the ground rely on—and are often manipulated by—a vast network of intelligence assets. The recurring cast of <em>Dark Wolf</em> expands the global scope of the series.
        </p>

        <h3>Luke Hemsworth as Jules Landry</h3>
        <p>
          Luke Hemsworth joins the cast as Jules Landry, a CIA officer who later operates as a contractor. Landry represents the bureaucratic and often ruthless nature of the intelligence community. His interactions with the SEALs highlight the friction between the operators executing the missions and the handlers dictating the terms from afar.
        </p>

        <h3>Dar Salim as Mohammed "Mo" Farooq</h3>
        <p>
          Dar Salim portrays Major Mohammed "Mo" Farooq, an Iraqi Special Operations Forces (ISOF) officer who later becomes a CIA contractor. This character adds vital international perspective and illustrates the crucial alliances formed on the ground between US forces and local specialized units during complex Middle Eastern operations.
        </p>

        <h3>Robert Wisdom as Jed Haverford</h3>
        <p>
          Veteran actor Robert Wisdom plays Jed Haverford, a CIA Iranian Operations Division spymaster. Haverford is a survivor of the Beirut Embassy bombing and a former 1st Cavalry Division soldier. His deep historical knowledge and hardened exterior make him a formidable player in the intelligence game, pulling strings that directly impact the SEAL platoons.
        </p>

        <h3>Rona-Lee Shimon as Eliza Perash</h3>
        <p>
          Rona-Lee Shimon (<em>Fauda</em>) stars as Eliza Perash, a veteran Mossad operative who becomes romantically involved with Ben Edwards. Her character introduces the high-stakes world of Israeli intelligence, adding a layer of romantic and operational complication to Edwards's already turbulent life.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Why These Casting Choices Matter</h2>
        <p>
          The <strong>cast of the terminal list: dark wolf</strong> represents a deliberate expansion of Jack Carr's geopolitical thriller universe. By bringing in heavy-hitters like Tom Hopper to play fan-favorite Raife Hastings, and integrating experienced actors like Robert Wisdom and Dar Salim, the series signals a commitment to authentic, complex storytelling.
        </p>
        <p>
          This ensemble isn't just about action; it's about the psychological toll of warfare and espionage. The interactions between Kitsch's Edwards and Pratt's Reece, knowing the tragedy that awaits them in the future, adds dramatic irony to every scene. Furthermore, the inclusion of Mossad and ISOF operatives indicates a narrative that respects the multifaceted, international nature of modern special operations. For those who enjoy intricate ensemble dynamics, much like the <a href="/tracker-cast">cast of investigative series like Tracker</a>, the interlocking relationships in <em>Dark Wolf</em> offer a compelling study in loyalty and betrayal.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
          <summary>Who stars in The Terminal List: Dark Wolf?</summary>
          <p>The series stars Taylor Kitsch as Ben Edwards, Tom Hopper as Raife Hastings, and features Chris Pratt reprising his role as James Reece.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Is Chris Pratt in The Terminal List: Dark Wolf?</summary>
          <p>Yes, Chris Pratt reprises his role as Lieutenant James Reece from the original 'The Terminal List' series as part of the main cast.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Who plays Raife Hastings in Dark Wolf?</summary>
          <p>Tom Hopper plays Lieutenant Raife Hastings, a US Navy SEAL and Troop Commander of Charlie Platoon with connections to the Selous Scouts.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>When does The Terminal List: Dark Wolf take place?</summary>
          <p>Dark Wolf serves as a prequel to the original series 'The Terminal List', focusing on the earlier missions and the development of the characters' relationships before the events of the first season.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Who are the recurring actors in Dark Wolf?</summary>
          <p>Recurring cast members include Dar Salim as Mohammed 'Mo' Farooq, Luke Hemsworth as Jules Landry, Robert Wisdom as Jed Haverford, and Rona-Lee Shimon as Eliza Perash.</p>
        </details>
      </section>
    </article>
  </div>

